36
00:01:35,120 --> 00:01:39,062
So to start with, I'm gonna define some things.

37
00:01:39,062 --> 00:01:41,604
I'm gonna say the word ambiguity a lot in this talk,

38
00:01:41,604 --> 00:01:45,046
so I wanna make sure that it's clear what I'm talking about.

39
00:01:47,076 --> 00:01:50,378
Ambiguity is when you don't have enough information

40
00:01:50,378 --> 00:01:51,659
to make good decisions.

41
00:01:51,659 --> 00:01:53,700
And it's different from risk.

42
00:01:53,700 --> 00:01:54,300
Here's how.

43
00:01:54,300 --> 00:01:54,961
So when you bet $100 on a coin flip,

44
00:01:54,961 --> 00:01:56,922
that's taking a risk.

45
00:01:56,922 --> 00:01:58,703
You have a ton of information.

46
00:01:58,703 --> 00:02:01,065
You know how many possible outcomes there are.

47
00:02:01,065 --> 00:02:03,806
You know the approximate odds of those outcomes.

48
00:02:03,806 --> 00:02:07,208
And you know what's gonna happen to you in either outcome.

49
00:02:07,208 --> 00:02:09,630
You're either gonna win $100 or you're gonna lose $100

50
00:02:09,630 --> 00:02:12,031
and there's about a 50-50 chance of that happening.

51
00:02:12,850 --> 00:02:14,912
Now humans love risk.

52
00:02:14,912 --> 00:02:15,792
We cannot get enough of it.

53
00:02:15,792 --> 00:02:18,534
There is, you know, there's billion dollar casino industries

54
00:02:18,534 --> 00:02:20,455
built around how much we completely love this.

55
00:02:20,455 --> 00:02:22,797
Like we love taking risks and taking chances

56
00:02:22,797 --> 00:02:24,498
when we know approximately the odds

57
00:02:24,498 --> 00:02:25,418
on what's gonna happen to us.

58
00:02:27,317 --> 00:02:31,600
Unfortunately, ambiguity is like betting $100 on

59
00:02:31,600 --> 00:02:32,820
if I roll the dice in this cup,

60
00:02:32,820 --> 00:02:34,542
are they gonna add up to at least 20?

61
00:02:34,542 --> 00:02:36,503
You have very little information

62
00:02:36,503 --> 00:02:37,544
on which to base that decision.

63
00:02:37,544 --> 00:02:38,885
You don't know how many dice I have

64
00:02:38,885 --> 00:02:41,366
or how many sides they have or what numbers are on them.

65
00:02:41,366 --> 00:02:42,867
You don't even know if I have dice in this cup at all.

66
00:02:42,867 --> 00:02:45,869
So you really don't have enough information

67
00:02:45,869 --> 00:02:47,210
to make that decision confidently.

68
00:02:47,210 --> 00:02:50,372
Now, as much as humans love risk and seek it out,

69
00:02:50,372 --> 00:02:52,434
we avoid ambiguity.

70
00:02:52,434 --> 00:02:53,515
We really don't like it.

71
00:02:53,515 --> 00:02:54,635
It makes us uncomfortable.

72
00:02:54,635 --> 00:02:56,156
It makes us unhappy and nervous.

73
00:02:57,107 --> 00:03:00,448
And unfortunately, in game development,

74
00:03:00,448 --> 00:03:03,028
almost every decision we make is that kind of

75
00:03:03,028 --> 00:03:04,429
ambiguous decision where we really

76
00:03:04,429 --> 00:03:05,429
don't have enough information.

77
00:03:05,429 --> 00:03:08,030
If you're trying to decide whether to include

78
00:03:08,030 --> 00:03:10,230
multiplayer in your game, for example,

79
00:03:10,230 --> 00:03:12,491
you don't know how much time and energy

80
00:03:12,491 --> 00:03:13,371
that's gonna cost you.

81
00:03:13,371 --> 00:03:15,551
You don't know how many bugs it's gonna introduce.

82
00:03:15,551 --> 00:03:17,072
You don't know if it's gonna be good or not,

83
00:03:17,072 --> 00:03:18,252
or if it's gonna be better or worse

84
00:03:18,252 --> 00:03:19,912
than the single player mode of your game.

85
00:03:20,532 --> 00:03:22,193
Maybe players will love it, maybe they'll hate it,

86
00:03:22,193 --> 00:03:23,454
maybe it'll raise your Metacritic,

87
00:03:23,454 --> 00:03:24,274
maybe it'll lower it, right?

88
00:03:24,274 --> 00:03:26,615
There's tons of possible outcomes

89
00:03:26,615 --> 00:03:28,476
and you really don't have a lot of information

90
00:03:28,476 --> 00:03:31,417
to use to predict how likely each of those outcomes are

91
00:03:31,417 --> 00:03:34,579
and you don't necessarily know what's gonna happen

92
00:03:34,579 --> 00:03:36,520
to you or your studio in any of those possible outcomes.

93
00:03:36,520 --> 00:03:40,122
So ambiguity is really stressful.

94
00:03:40,122 --> 00:03:41,762
We don't like it, we try to avoid it,

95
00:03:41,762 --> 00:03:44,143
but in game development, we deal with it constantly.

96
00:03:47,849 --> 00:03:50,771
And not only is ambiguity scary and uncomfortable,

97
00:03:50,771 --> 00:03:54,153
to ship your game, you have to make all the decisions

98
00:03:54,153 --> 00:03:56,035
