00:04:57,930 --> 00:05:02,591
Which is also when we're growing the most and learning the most ourselves and becoming better game developers, right?

125
00:05:02,591 --> 00:05:07,813
So we're we're again we're dealing with us all the time and especially those of us working in VR

126
00:05:07,813 --> 00:05:13,574
There's tons of ambiguity there because nobody even knows yet like what good VR games are or anything about it, right?

127
00:05:13,574 --> 00:05:18,215
So tons and tons of ambiguity and okay, how many people here are working on a really ambiguous game?

128
00:05:18,215 --> 00:05:19,375
We have tons of unknowns to deal with

129
00:05:21,520 --> 00:05:25,101
Yeah, so you're all in good company.

130
00:05:25,101 --> 00:05:26,561
All right, let's talk about why that's hard.

131
00:05:26,561 --> 00:05:29,121
You know, it's hard to make good decisions

132
00:05:29,121 --> 00:05:31,162
when you just don't know what's going to happen.

133
00:05:31,162 --> 00:05:34,402
And there are a lot of things that are unknown

134
00:05:34,402 --> 00:05:35,763
when you're making a game.

135
00:05:35,763 --> 00:05:36,743
Some of them you can control

136
00:05:36,743 --> 00:05:37,923
and some of them you really can't, right?

137
00:05:37,923 --> 00:05:39,784
So first of all, like what is your game?

138
00:05:39,784 --> 00:05:41,284
What game are you making?

139
00:05:41,284 --> 00:05:42,084
What's it gonna be like?

140
00:05:42,084 --> 00:05:43,444
What is the vision for your game?

141
00:05:43,444 --> 00:05:44,705
A lot of times that's super ambiguous.

142
00:05:46,411 --> 00:05:47,512
And then how do you make it?

143
00:05:47,512 --> 00:05:48,874
Like how do you execute on that vision

144
00:05:48,874 --> 00:05:50,916
and what's going to actually happen

145
00:05:50,916 --> 00:05:52,378
when you sit down and start making this game?

146
00:05:52,378 --> 00:05:55,762
And then even things like team roles and team organization,

147
00:05:55,762 --> 00:05:58,445
like who's responsible for what on your project,

148
00:05:58,445 --> 00:05:59,306
who's in charge of what,

149
00:05:59,306 --> 00:06:00,607
and who gets to make which decisions.

150
00:06:00,607 --> 00:06:01,728
That can be super ambiguous.

151
00:06:03,705 --> 00:06:05,145
And then things you don't have control over,

152
00:06:05,145 --> 00:06:06,245
like your partner's decisions.

153
00:06:06,245 --> 00:06:08,506
Maybe your publisher decides tomorrow morning

154
00:06:08,506 --> 00:06:10,166
that they really hate first-person shooters now.

155
00:06:10,166 --> 00:06:10,446
Who knows?

156
00:06:10,446 --> 00:06:12,267
Anything could happen, right?

157
00:06:12,267 --> 00:06:14,867
And again, you don't know the possible outcomes

158
00:06:14,867 --> 00:06:17,428
or necessarily what's gonna happen to you and your team

159
00:06:17,428 --> 00:06:20,029
in any of those outcomes.

160
00:06:20,029 --> 00:06:21,009
Market forces.

161
00:06:21,009 --> 00:06:23,630
Maybe a new game comes out

162
00:06:23,630 --> 00:06:24,850
that redefines your genre tomorrow,

163
00:06:24,850 --> 00:06:26,310
and you have to sit down and decide

164
00:06:26,310 --> 00:06:29,231
if you're going to redesign your game or not,

165
00:06:29,231 --> 00:06:30,831
