00:10:27,986 --> 00:10:31,648
If you don't have a clear, well-defined, and well-understood vision for your game,

256
00:10:31,648 --> 00:10:33,590
you should do that first. That should be your top priority.

257
00:10:33,590 --> 00:10:36,431
And really, nothing else I'm going to talk about matters if you don't have that.

258
00:10:36,431 --> 00:10:41,515
If you haven't already, I really encourage everyone who's a producer

259
00:10:41,515 --> 00:10:44,416
to read the Game Outcomes Project. It was a series of articles.

260
00:10:44,416 --> 00:10:47,658
I'll link to it in the notes. It was published a couple of years ago.

261
00:10:48,264 --> 00:10:52,427
Paul Tozer and his team surveyed hundreds of game developers and they asked them questions

262
00:10:52,427 --> 00:10:56,951
about their process, how they made decisions on their team, how their team was structured,

263
00:10:56,951 --> 00:11:00,674
a bunch of different questions, and then they correlated the answers to those questions

264
00:11:00,674 --> 00:11:05,458
against the success of the finished games. And not just Metacritic, but Return on Investment

265
00:11:05,458 --> 00:11:11,263
and how well that game met the expectations of the development team themselves. And what they found...

266
00:11:11,768 --> 00:11:13,790
was that the strongest correlating factor

267
00:11:13,790 --> 00:11:17,892
to a successful game was a viable, compelling, clear,

268
00:11:17,892 --> 00:11:19,814
and well-communicated shared vision.

269
00:11:19,814 --> 00:11:23,236
Games that had this were successful,

270
00:11:23,236 --> 00:11:25,557
and games that didn't have this were not successful.

271
00:11:25,557 --> 00:11:28,679
So if you don't have this clear, strong, agreed-on vision

272
00:11:28,679 --> 00:11:31,221
for your game, then you need to get one.

273
00:11:31,221 --> 00:11:33,142
As a producer, that is your top job.

274
00:11:33,142 --> 00:11:34,923
If you do have one, then you can use

275
00:11:34,923 --> 00:11:37,405
it to drive, again, all of those execution decisions

276
00:11:37,405 --> 00:11:39,086
and get rid of the other ambiguity on the project.

277
00:11:41,958 --> 00:11:44,523
All right, similarly, ambiguity is less negative

278
00:11:44,523 --> 00:11:47,949
and can even be positive if you're early on in development.

279
00:11:47,949 --> 00:11:49,852
So remember, ambiguity is when you don't

280
00:11:49,852 --> 00:11:50,654
have enough information.

281
00:11:50,654 --> 00:11:52,397
So this is the cone of uncertainty.

282
00:11:53,159 --> 00:11:55,661
And early on in a project, there are tons of unknowns

283
00:11:55,661 --> 00:11:56,662
and tons of uncertainty, right?

284
00:11:56,662 --> 00:11:57,683
You don't know what game you're making,

285
00:11:57,683 --> 00:11:59,225
you don't know maybe what engine you're gonna use,

286
00:11:59,225 --> 00:12:00,947
you don't know what the main character will look like.

287
00:12:00,947 --> 00:12:02,989
You have to develop all of that information over time.

288
00:12:02,989 --> 00:12:05,992
And then by the time you ship, you know every single thing.

289
00:12:05,992 --> 00:12:07,574
Or you've decided everything,

290
00:12:07,574 --> 00:12:09,636
everything is precisely defined.

291
00:12:09,636 --> 00:12:12,279
To get there, you have to drive this cone down over time.

292
00:12:12,860 --> 00:12:15,582
Now, the thing is, this cone does not narrow on its own, right?

293
00:12:15,582 --> 00:12:16,783
It wants to get wider.

294
00:12:16,783 --> 00:12:20,966
People want to play around, they want to innovate, they want to come up with cool new stuff.

295
00:12:20,966 --> 00:12:24,549
But you as the producer have to make sure that the cone is trending in the right direction

296
00:12:24,549 --> 00:12:26,110
so that it gets to zero by the time you ship.

297
00:12:26,110 --> 00:12:31,714
And again, if you have time to be in pre-production and, you know, innovate and come up with cool

298
00:12:31,714 --> 00:12:33,576
stuff and try things, then do that.

299
00:12:33,576 --> 00:12:34,776
Like, you know, that's fine.

300
00:12:34,776 --> 00:12:37,859
Just, again, as a producer, you have to keep track of where you are and where things are

301
00:12:37,859 --> 00:12:38,179
trending.

302
00:12:41,122 --> 00:12:44,089
And then third, whether or not ambiguity is a problem

303
00:12:44,089 --> 00:12:45,172
depends on your constraints.

304
00:12:45,172 --> 00:12:46,616
So this is the iron triangle,

305
00:12:46,616 --> 00:12:50,085
and you may have heard of it as fast, cheaper, good, pick two.

306
00:12:51,195 --> 00:12:53,496
But in game development, usually we have to pick all three,

307
00:12:53,496 --> 00:12:54,736
and we have to ship a good game,

308
00:12:54,736 --> 00:12:56,657
and it has to have a bunch of features in it

309
00:12:56,657 --> 00:12:58,017
that the publisher demands or whatever.

310
00:12:58,017 --> 00:13:01,238
So it can be really difficult.

311
00:13:01,238 --> 00:13:03,179
And really this iron triangle,

312
00:13:03,179 --> 00:13:05,320
it's a way to think about your constraints.

313
00:13:05,320 --> 00:13:08,041
So the smaller your budget is, the shorter your schedule,

314
00:13:08,041 --> 00:13:10,101
and the more features you have to include,

315
00:13:10,101 --> 00:13:12,102
the less room you have for ambiguity,

316
00:13:12,102 --> 00:13:14,343
the less room you have for that innovation and creativity,

317
00:13:14,343 --> 00:13:16,063
and the more you just have to focus on executing.

318
00:13:17,854 --> 00:13:22,197
If, you know, again, if you have all the time and money you need to prototype for three

319
00:13:22,197 --> 00:13:25,679
years and be in pre-production, then, you know, go for it and knock yourselves out.

320
00:13:25,679 --> 00:13:28,841
But if you don't, then you have to really tighten things down.

321
00:13:28,841 --> 00:13:32,483
The least ambiguous game I ever worked on was an expansion pack to a sequel.

322
00:13:33,514 --> 00:13:36,156
and the budget was small, the schedule was super tight,

323
00:13:36,156 --> 00:13:38,757
and because it was based on existing games,

324
00:13:38,757 --> 00:13:40,338
we didn't have a lot of room for innovation, right?

325
00:13:40,338 --> 00:13:43,039
We knew a lot about the game we were gonna make.

326
00:13:43,039 --> 00:13:44,200
So we just executed, and it went really well.

327
00:13:44,200 --> 00:13:46,501
You know, it wasn't the most innovative game ever,

328
00:13:46,501 --> 00:13:47,722
but it was fine, and we were able to, you know,

329
00:13:47,722 --> 00:13:49,823
keep the ambiguity really low and just execute.

330
00:13:49,823 --> 00:13:51,024
And then finally, ambiguity is a problem

331
00:13:51,024 --> 00:13:51,784
if it's causing problems on your project.

332
00:13:59,768 --> 00:14:02,789
So I'm going to talk about five kind of major problems

333
00:14:02,789 --> 00:14:04,070
that can result from too much ambiguity.

334
00:14:04,070 --> 00:14:08,731
And I'm going to talk about them and give you some tools

335
00:14:08,731 --> 00:14:10,252
that you can use to either, again,

336
00:14:10,252 --> 00:14:13,073
avoid these problems or fix them.

337
00:14:13,073 --> 00:14:15,573
So first of all, churning without progress.

338
00:14:15,573 --> 00:14:17,754
This is when you have too much ambiguity

339
00:14:17,754 --> 00:14:21,195
to be able to actually make real progress on your game.

340
00:14:21,195 --> 00:14:22,435
No matter how hard you work,

341
00:14:22,435 --> 00:14:23,096
it just kind of feels like

342
00:14:23,096 --> 00:14:24,036
you're not really getting anywhere.

343
00:14:25,882 --> 00:14:27,422
And second, feature creep.

344
00:14:27,422 --> 00:14:28,823
You don't really know what your game is,

345
00:14:28,823 --> 00:14:30,064
so you just kind of add more stuff,

346
00:14:30,064 --> 00:14:30,964
hoping that you'll make it better.

347
00:14:30,964 --> 00:14:31,425
And then team anxiety.

348
00:14:31,425 --> 00:14:32,365
Your team is afraid of what might happen

349
00:14:32,365 --> 00:14:35,587
because they can't really predict outcomes,

350
00:14:35,587 --> 00:14:38,649
so they get kind of nervous and anxious

351
00:14:38,649 --> 00:14:40,550
and they aren't able to do their best work.

352
00:14:40,550 --> 00:14:41,150
Conflict and resentment.

353
00:14:41,150 --> 00:14:42,131
You feel like the ambiguity is somebody's fault,

354
00:14:42,131 --> 00:14:44,992
so you have to blame somebody.

355
00:14:44,992 --> 00:14:48,294
Obviously, it's not my fault because I'm doing my best,

356
00:14:48,294 --> 00:14:50,936
so it must be somebody's fault.

357
00:14:52,489 --> 00:14:53,749
And then indecision.

358
00:14:53,749 --> 00:14:57,850
You don't have enough information to make good decisions, so you just don't make them.

359
00:14:57,850 --> 00:15:01,751
So obviously most of the time the problems aren't going to be as clear as I'm going to

360
00:15:01,751 --> 00:15:03,032
lay them out here.

361
00:15:03,032 --> 00:15:05,632
They're not going to be super clear cut.

362
00:15:05,632 --> 00:15:12,554
But again, even the best well-managed projects with super clear goals are going to run into

363
00:15:12,554 --> 00:15:16,635
some ambiguity that's going to make your team maybe start churning or start getting anxious.

364
00:15:17,409 --> 00:15:22,554
And sometimes these are small isolated problems that are easy to fix but sometimes if they're

365
00:15:22,554 --> 00:15:25,857
not addressed, they can grow into big giant major problems that will destroy your team.

366
00:15:25,857 --> 00:15:30,662
So let's go over some things that you as a producer can do to fix these problems before

367
00:15:30,662 --> 00:15:31,223
they get that big.

368
00:15:34,310 --> 00:15:36,512
All right, so churning without progress

369
00:15:36,512 --> 00:15:39,735
is probably the most damaging result of ambiguity, right?

370
00:15:39,735 --> 00:15:42,318
So this is when you're doing a bunch of things,

371
00:15:42,318 --> 00:15:43,879
but you're not really getting anywhere.

372
00:15:43,879 --> 00:15:44,920
And this is usually, again,

373
00:15:44,920 --> 00:15:46,622
because your vision isn't clear enough

374
00:15:46,622 --> 00:15:48,444
to know if you're really driving toward it or not,

375
00:15:48,444 --> 00:15:49,886
or if you're getting closer to your vision or not.

376
00:15:49,886 --> 00:15:52,228
So here are some problems to watch for.

377
00:15:52,228 --> 00:15:54,490
First of all, if your game isn't changing.

378
00:15:55,483 --> 00:15:57,964
Maybe you have weekly design reviews or regular reviews

379
00:15:57,964 --> 00:16:00,045
where you look at the game and it's not really changing,

380
00:16:00,045 --> 00:16:01,246
it's not any different.

381
00:16:01,246 --> 00:16:03,046
People are playing on their phones during design reviews

382
00:16:03,046 --> 00:16:05,867
because there's just nothing interesting happening.

383
00:16:05,867 --> 00:16:07,508
Or your milestones slip.

384
00:16:07,508 --> 00:16:08,308
People can't really tell you

385
00:16:08,308 --> 00:16:09,309
when they're gonna get something done

386
00:16:09,309 --> 00:16:10,649
because they're kind of blocked by something

387
00:16:10,649 --> 00:16:11,390
they can't really define.

388
00:16:14,243 --> 00:16:19,665
Rat-holing or bike-shedding, these are both jargon terms for focusing on a small problem

389
00:16:19,665 --> 00:16:23,487
that's easy to fix while ignoring a gigantic problem that's hard to fix.

390
00:16:23,487 --> 00:16:27,789
So you haven't decided which engine you're going to use yet, but you have these giant

391
00:16:27,789 --> 00:16:29,890
epic reply-all email threads about which font to use.

392
00:16:29,890 --> 00:16:32,992
That's a much easier problem and something people really like focusing on and diving

393
00:16:32,992 --> 00:16:36,633
into because they just want to really not think about the fact that there's this huge

394
00:16:36,633 --> 00:16:37,594
problem they haven't fixed yet.

395
00:16:37,594 --> 00:16:39,415
Go to Beadaholique.com for all of your beading supply needs!

396
00:16:41,650 --> 00:16:43,752
And last, you know, throwing away work.

397
00:16:43,752 --> 00:16:46,414
So, I was a level designer on a game

398
00:16:46,414 --> 00:16:48,976
where the level design team was pumping out levels

399
00:16:48,976 --> 00:16:50,857
like clockwork, so each of us were making

400
00:16:50,857 --> 00:16:52,038
three levels every three weeks.

401
00:16:52,038 --> 00:16:54,260
And they were good levels, like we were doing good work,

402
00:16:54,260 --> 00:16:56,582
you know, we were having an okay time,

403
00:16:56,582 --> 00:16:58,343
we were delivering very regularly,

404
00:16:58,343 --> 00:17:01,966
but the story for the game wasn't written yet at all.

405
00:17:02,254 --> 00:17:03,975
the monster behaviors weren't defined.

406
00:17:03,975 --> 00:17:06,437
There were tons of things about the game

407
00:17:06,437 --> 00:17:08,078
that nobody knew yet.

408
00:17:08,078 --> 00:17:10,480
So, you know, everything we were

409
00:17:10,480 --> 00:17:12,542
doing was basically destined to be thrown away.

410
00:17:12,542 --> 00:17:14,523
The other problem was

411
00:17:14,523 --> 00:17:15,925
of the levels we were making, two out of

412
00:17:15,925 --> 00:17:18,166
every three of them were rejected by the lead designer

413
00:17:18,166 --> 00:17:19,948
as like, no, this isn't really what I'm thinking.

414
00:17:19,948 --> 00:17:21,189
So, we were

415
00:17:21,189 --> 00:17:24,191
completely spinning our wheels. We were doing

416
00:17:24,191 --> 00:17:26,353
our best, but it wasn't really going

417
00:17:26,353 --> 00:17:28,615
anywhere, and ultimately all of that work was thrown away.

418
00:17:30,207 --> 00:17:32,209
Remember that people don't get into game development

419
00:17:32,209 --> 00:17:33,450
because they're lazy, right?

420
00:17:33,450 --> 00:17:34,651
They get into game development because they

421
00:17:34,651 --> 00:17:36,272
want to make awesome things.

422
00:17:36,272 --> 00:17:37,013
And they will do that.

423
00:17:37,013 --> 00:17:38,194
Even if you don't have your clear vision

424
00:17:38,194 --> 00:17:39,615
that they can work towards,

425
00:17:39,615 --> 00:17:41,917
they're going to do their best to do good work.

426
00:17:41,917 --> 00:17:43,978
And throwing that work away is a huge waste

427
00:17:43,978 --> 00:17:45,359
and it's really demoralizing.

428
00:17:45,359 --> 00:17:47,181
So you shouldn't do it.

429
00:17:47,181 --> 00:17:49,603
Here's what you can do as a producer to fix that situation.

430
00:17:49,603 --> 00:17:52,385
So again, I'm going to say this over and over

431
00:17:52,385 --> 00:17:54,827
and over and over, drive towards a clear vision.

432
00:17:55,671 --> 00:17:59,578
Remember that the one thing that will help your team be successful is to have a strong, clear vision.

433
00:17:59,578 --> 00:18:01,943
And if you don't have that, make that your top priority.

434
00:18:03,460 --> 00:18:05,741
Now second, if you do have a clear vision for your game,

435
00:18:05,741 --> 00:18:07,322
but you still feel like your team is kind of spinning

436
00:18:07,322 --> 00:18:09,502
their wheels and not really getting anywhere,

437
00:18:09,502 --> 00:18:12,984
you know, maybe set shorter term goals or prototype goals

438
00:18:12,984 --> 00:18:16,045
to where your team can get in the habit of finishing things

439
00:18:16,045 --> 00:18:16,985
and where you can build something

440
00:18:16,985 --> 00:18:18,325
that you can really play test.

441
00:18:18,325 --> 00:18:20,546
So, you know, let's say you build a vertical slice,

442
00:18:20,546 --> 00:18:22,327
which is where you sort of try to build something

443
00:18:22,327 --> 00:18:24,067
that reflects your final game vision

444
00:18:24,067 --> 00:18:25,988
to the point where it's playable.

445
00:18:25,988 --> 00:18:27,548
And then your team can play it and find out,

446
00:18:27,548 --> 00:18:29,049
okay, what is really good about this?

447
00:18:29,049 --> 00:18:30,609
What's the strengths of our game vision?

448
00:18:30,609 --> 00:18:31,790
What are the things that players

449
00:18:31,790 --> 00:18:33,030
are gonna really fall in love with?

450
00:18:33,590 --> 00:18:36,611
And then also, what are the things that took up a bunch of time and effort but that really

451
00:18:36,611 --> 00:18:37,752
aren't that good?

452
00:18:37,752 --> 00:18:41,653
Maybe we should cut those things and focus on the things that are awesome.

453
00:18:41,653 --> 00:18:46,935
And then third, is your team exploring cool, innovative ideas during pre-production?

454
00:18:46,935 --> 00:18:47,955
You know, that's fine.

455
00:18:47,955 --> 00:18:50,696
Or are they totally lost in the woods?

456
00:18:50,696 --> 00:18:55,078
Remember that the difference between exploring and being lost is that if you're exploring,

457
00:18:55,078 --> 00:18:58,399
you're going towards something and you can kind of tell if you're getting closer to it.

458
00:18:58,399 --> 00:19:01,360
But if you're just lost, you're lost and you're not really getting anywhere.

459
00:19:02,277 --> 00:19:08,265
Again, if you have the time and money to be lost for a little while, that can be really useful.

460
00:19:08,265 --> 00:19:09,807
But if you don't, make sure that you're not.

461
00:19:09,807 --> 00:19:09,987
And then

462
00:19:14,123 --> 00:19:17,424
If you're kind of churning, but it looks like it might be temporary and you're not really

463
00:19:17,424 --> 00:19:19,805
sure, you can do something called time boxing.

464
00:19:19,805 --> 00:19:23,245
And that's where you say, okay, we don't know yet if we're going to do multiplayer, we're

465
00:19:23,245 --> 00:19:27,666
trying some things, we're doing some prototypes, but if we haven't decided by May, then we

466
00:19:27,666 --> 00:19:30,847
should really start worrying because our schedule is not going to let us spend any more time

467
00:19:30,847 --> 00:19:31,907
on this, right?

468
00:19:31,907 --> 00:19:34,828
Or even if your team is reluctant, or if you don't want to bring that up to your team,

469
00:19:34,828 --> 00:19:37,088
maybe just internally yourself as the producer.

470
00:19:37,589 --> 00:19:40,191
You can say, okay, if we haven't decided by May,

471
00:19:40,191 --> 00:19:42,193
I'm personally gonna start worrying and freaking out

472
00:19:42,193 --> 00:19:43,375
and raising this to people, right?

473
00:19:43,375 --> 00:19:46,097
I'm gonna raise some flags if we haven't decided this

474
00:19:46,097 --> 00:19:48,259
in two months or whatever.

475
00:19:48,259 --> 00:19:50,822
You know, execution always takes longer than you think,

476
00:19:50,822 --> 00:19:52,304
especially if you're doing something new,

477
00:19:52,304 --> 00:19:54,486
which you probably are, so keep that in mind

478
00:19:54,486 --> 00:19:56,608
and just try as a producer to be a little conservative

479
00:19:56,608 --> 00:19:57,128
with your schedule.

480
00:19:59,062 --> 00:20:03,505
And then last, if your team is so stuck that they can't make progress, you can try something

481
00:20:03,505 --> 00:20:03,766
drastic.

482
00:20:03,766 --> 00:20:08,610
So I don't know how many of you are familiar with Scrum, but Scrum is a project management

483
00:20:08,610 --> 00:20:11,752
system that was developed specifically to unstick stuck teams.

484
00:20:11,752 --> 00:20:16,437
I think people use it a little too much, probably more than they should.

485
00:20:16,717 --> 00:20:20,200
But, if your team is super stuck, it might be worth trying something like that.

486
00:20:20,200 --> 00:20:24,864
Just change up the way you do your process, change up the way you schedule or track work

487
00:20:24,864 --> 00:20:25,745
or something like that.

488
00:20:25,745 --> 00:20:28,507
If you're having daily stand-ups, maybe change to weekly or something.

489
00:20:28,507 --> 00:20:32,110
Try changing things so that maybe it kicks your team out of their deadlock.

490
00:20:32,110 --> 00:20:34,933
But again, the most important thing is having a clear vision.

491
00:20:34,933 --> 00:20:41,118
So I'm going to talk about a tool for developing and protecting that game vision.

492
00:20:44,161 --> 00:20:45,282
Okay, so these are pillars.

493
00:20:45,282 --> 00:20:47,803
I made these up, so they're not very good.

494
00:20:47,803 --> 00:20:50,244
So this is a sample pillars for a made up game.

495
00:20:50,244 --> 00:20:53,906
The player is a powerful commander of a dragon army.

496
00:20:53,906 --> 00:20:57,047
Players can battle their armies while waiting for the bus.

497
00:20:57,047 --> 00:20:58,988
And players use their huge inventory of magic items

498
00:20:58,988 --> 00:20:59,668
to power up their dragons.

499
00:21:00,445 --> 00:21:02,606
Okay, so again, not the best pillars ever,

500
00:21:02,606 --> 00:21:05,067
but reading them, you can envision

501
00:21:05,067 --> 00:21:06,107
what this game would be like, right?

502
00:21:06,107 --> 00:21:07,728
And if you're working on this game,

503
00:21:07,728 --> 00:21:09,729
you can kind of use these as a yardstick

504
00:21:09,729 --> 00:21:11,489
to think about the work you're doing, right?

505
00:21:11,489 --> 00:21:12,850
If you're working on the UI

506
00:21:12,850 --> 00:21:14,530
for giving your dragons commands,

507
00:21:14,530 --> 00:21:16,451
that's really important, that supports the top pillar.

508
00:21:16,451 --> 00:21:20,373
If you're working on customizable dragon houses, right,

509
00:21:20,373 --> 00:21:22,073
that doesn't really support any of the pillars,

510
00:21:22,073 --> 00:21:24,714
it's probably extraneous and you don't need to do it.

511
00:21:24,714 --> 00:21:26,655
So pillars are kind of like a distillation

512
00:21:26,655 --> 00:21:29,376
of your entire design doc into a couple of bullets.

513
00:21:29,747 --> 00:21:31,027
and they're easy to communicate,

514
00:21:31,027 --> 00:21:33,289
they're easy for your team to remember and understand,

515
00:21:33,289 --> 00:21:35,590
and you can kind of use them as a ruler

516
00:21:35,590 --> 00:21:36,751
for the work that you're doing.

517
00:21:36,751 --> 00:21:39,052
They're also kind of like a pitch, right?

518
00:21:39,052 --> 00:21:40,533
If you told someone about these pillars,

519
00:21:40,533 --> 00:21:41,754
if you were in an elevator with someone,

520
00:21:41,754 --> 00:21:44,075
you told them this, you would know pretty quickly

521
00:21:44,075 --> 00:21:45,676
if they were excited about the game or not,

522
00:21:45,676 --> 00:21:46,957
what about it excites them,

523
00:21:46,957 --> 00:21:49,278
what are they interested in learning more about, right?

524
00:21:49,278 --> 00:21:51,720
So it's kind of a distillation of what is your game

525
00:21:51,720 --> 00:21:52,880
down into a very short list.

526
00:21:55,458 --> 00:21:59,363
I talk about pillars and game vision all the time.

527
00:21:59,363 --> 00:22:03,167
I really can't shut up about them.

528
00:22:03,167 --> 00:22:04,629
And this is why I think that this is so important.

529
00:22:04,629 --> 00:22:09,335
If you want to build a ship, don't drum up people to collect wood and don't assign them

530
00:22:09,335 --> 00:22:13,521
tasks and work, but rather teach them to long for the endless immensity of the sea.

531
00:22:15,277 --> 00:22:18,778
I would bet that most people on your team did not get into game development because

532
00:22:18,778 --> 00:22:20,479
they really like following directions.

533
00:22:20,479 --> 00:22:25,422
They get into game development because they long to make amazing, great games.

534
00:22:25,422 --> 00:22:31,224
So make sure you have a vision for a game that your team will long to make and that

535
00:22:31,224 --> 00:22:35,687
players will long to play and that your team can believe in and be proud of and pour all

536
00:22:35,687 --> 00:22:36,767
of that creative energy into.

537
00:22:40,150 --> 00:22:42,072
Because if you don't, you'll end up with feature creep.

538
00:22:42,072 --> 00:22:45,794
And again, this is where you aren't really sure

539
00:22:45,794 --> 00:22:48,055
what your game is, so you kind of throw in

540
00:22:48,055 --> 00:22:50,737
random cool stuff, hoping that it will be good.

541
00:22:50,737 --> 00:22:51,317
It won't.

542
00:22:51,317 --> 00:22:53,899
It will make it worse.

543
00:22:53,899 --> 00:22:56,581
Or your creative director gets super duper excited

544
00:22:56,581 --> 00:22:57,401
about every new idea.

545
00:22:57,401 --> 00:22:59,923
She comes across and nobody can tell her no.

546
00:22:59,923 --> 00:23:02,044
Or you don't know if you should tell her no or not.

547
00:23:02,044 --> 00:23:03,445
Or what you should say no to.

548
00:23:05,722 --> 00:23:09,684
Or you're halfway through production and your schedule is clearly completely impossible,

549
00:23:09,684 --> 00:23:11,125
but you don't really know what to cut.

550
00:23:11,125 --> 00:23:14,186
You don't know which features are going to have the most payoff and which ones are going

551
00:23:14,186 --> 00:23:16,667
to be big risks that end up not being very good.

552
00:23:16,667 --> 00:23:22,969
I worked on a really big AAA game that actually had a super clear, strong vision, a great

553
00:23:22,969 --> 00:23:26,991
vision that everyone really loved, but it was a big team.

554
00:23:26,991 --> 00:23:28,272
We hadn't really worked together before.

555
00:23:29,198 --> 00:23:30,960
The leadership was a little bit fractured.

556
00:23:30,960 --> 00:23:32,581
The cost of failure was super high.

557
00:23:32,581 --> 00:23:35,703
There were a lot of stakeholders at the publisher level

558
00:23:35,703 --> 00:23:37,284
that were super invested in the game.

559
00:23:37,284 --> 00:23:40,246
They wanted us to add a bunch of stuff.

560
00:23:40,246 --> 00:23:43,248
You know, we added all these expensive features

561
00:23:43,248 --> 00:23:45,610
to the game that it didn't really need,

562
00:23:45,610 --> 00:23:47,411
that cost a ton of time and effort.

563
00:23:47,411 --> 00:23:48,792
And then, you know, we would do these demos

564
00:23:48,792 --> 00:23:50,013
to the stakeholders who wanted them

565
00:23:50,013 --> 00:23:51,213
and they would kind of get excited,

566
00:23:51,213 --> 00:23:53,735
but it was just this like total waste of time.

567
00:23:54,721 --> 00:23:56,983
And then the features that were core to the vision of the game,

568
00:23:56,983 --> 00:23:59,484
which again was super good, were getting short-changed

569
00:23:59,484 --> 00:24:01,246
and not really worked on as much.

570
00:24:01,246 --> 00:24:04,368
So, you know, this caused a lot of tension and infighting

571
00:24:04,368 --> 00:24:06,729
and frustration among the team because we could see

572
00:24:06,729 --> 00:24:08,050
that the really cool game we were thinking of

573
00:24:08,050 --> 00:24:08,611
just wasn't getting done.

574
00:24:08,611 --> 00:24:09,371
So, what can you do in this situation?

575
00:24:14,921 --> 00:24:18,524
First of all, again, ambiguity is when you don't have enough information to make good

576
00:24:18,524 --> 00:24:19,545
decisions.

577
00:24:19,545 --> 00:24:22,007
So you can reduce ambiguity by getting information.

578
00:24:22,007 --> 00:24:27,231
One way to do that is to get data by sitting down with your team and figuring out how much

579
00:24:27,231 --> 00:24:29,132
each of these features that you want to make are going to cost you.

580
00:24:29,132 --> 00:24:30,673
There's lots of ways to do this.

581
00:24:30,673 --> 00:24:34,536
This is something that's, you know, there's a lot of articles written about.

582
00:24:34,536 --> 00:24:37,139
But you basically sit down with your teams, you list the features you want to do, and

583
00:24:37,139 --> 00:24:40,041
you come up with some way to estimate the cost of each of them.

584
00:24:40,041 --> 00:24:41,462
So it can be man months.

585
00:24:41,862 --> 00:24:43,463
It can be arbitrary made up numbers.

586
00:24:43,463 --> 00:24:45,744
It doesn't really matter.

587
00:24:45,744 --> 00:24:48,204
But if you can estimate and assign some number

588
00:24:48,204 --> 00:24:49,865
to the cost of things, again, it'll

589
00:24:49,865 --> 00:24:53,926
give you a little peek inside this dice cup, which can really

590
00:24:53,926 --> 00:24:54,647
help you make decisions.

591
00:24:54,647 --> 00:24:58,468
And then honestly evaluate each feature

592
00:24:58,468 --> 00:24:59,408
against your game vision.

593
00:24:59,408 --> 00:25:01,189
So if you have pillars, or a design doc,

594
00:25:01,189 --> 00:25:05,210
or a vision statement, you can evaluate those features.

595
00:25:05,210 --> 00:25:07,311
Do they really support our game vision or not?

596
00:25:07,311 --> 00:25:08,611
Are they extraneous?

597
00:25:08,611 --> 00:25:10,652
Can we cut them and not really lose anything?

598
00:25:12,018 --> 00:25:14,999
And remember that if your constraints are tight, the tighter your constraints, the less

599
00:25:14,999 --> 00:25:16,459
you can afford this extra stuff.

600
00:25:16,459 --> 00:25:19,680
The more you have to focus on really just what do your pillars absolutely need?

601
00:25:19,680 --> 00:25:26,202
And then, you know, you can work with your team to rank features based on these two aspects,

602
00:25:26,202 --> 00:25:26,942
cost and value.

603
00:25:26,942 --> 00:25:32,003
Be brutally honest about how much this stuff is going to cost and how much you really need

604
00:25:32,003 --> 00:25:32,063
it.

605
00:25:33,371 --> 00:25:38,992
Here's an example of a feature list ranked by benefit to the game, so this could be just

606
00:25:38,992 --> 00:25:43,634
how much it supports the pillars or how good it is, and then secondly by effort, so this

607
00:25:43,634 --> 00:25:47,995
could be man hours, it could be man months, it could be just some arbitrary number, and

608
00:25:47,995 --> 00:25:52,436
then based on those two numbers develop a value, some value estimate for how valuable

609
00:25:52,436 --> 00:25:54,437
is this feature to my game, what's the return on investment?

610
00:25:56,335 --> 00:26:00,276
If you can use this to really generate your priority list,

611
00:26:00,276 --> 00:26:01,437
start at the top and work down,

612
00:26:01,437 --> 00:26:02,617
and then realize, okay, you know what,

613
00:26:02,617 --> 00:26:04,838
these two features, they seem cool,

614
00:26:04,838 --> 00:26:06,739
but they really either don't have a lot of value to the game

615
00:26:06,739 --> 00:26:08,099
or they're just gonna cost us too much.

616
00:26:08,099 --> 00:26:09,980
We don't need to do them.

617
00:26:09,980 --> 00:26:13,041
Make sure that you have some way to add numbers to things

618
00:26:13,041 --> 00:26:15,102
so that your team can really agree, right?

619
00:26:15,102 --> 00:26:17,023
And again, these numbers do not have to be super precise.

620
00:26:17,023 --> 00:26:18,383
They don't have to accurately reflect

621
00:26:18,383 --> 00:26:20,764
like the exact number of days you're gonna spend on it.

622
00:26:20,764 --> 00:26:22,445
But just having numbers so that you can have

623
00:26:22,445 --> 00:26:23,545
a conversation about it with your team

624
00:26:23,545 --> 00:26:24,526
is gonna be really valuable.

625
00:26:25,759 --> 00:26:31,703
There's a GDC 2015 talk about doing this on the Witcher 3, which is super interesting.

626
00:26:31,703 --> 00:26:36,406
I'm going to link to it in the notes and I recommend checking that out if you're interested

627
00:26:36,406 --> 00:26:37,046
in learning more about this.

628
00:26:37,046 --> 00:26:37,326
All right.

629
00:26:37,326 --> 00:26:40,208
So third, team anxiety.

630
00:26:40,208 --> 00:26:46,012
This is when your team just gets overwhelmed by the amount of ambiguity and they get unhappy,

631
00:26:46,012 --> 00:26:49,314
they get negative, or maybe they just kind of give up and stop putting so much effort

632
00:26:49,314 --> 00:26:51,555
in because they feel like their effort isn't going to the right place.

633
00:26:53,265 --> 00:26:54,405
And maybe that's because they don't know

634
00:26:54,405 --> 00:26:55,886
what they're expected to do.

635
00:26:55,886 --> 00:26:58,507
They don't know what success looks like for them.

636
00:26:58,507 --> 00:27:00,649
Maybe this is because your game vision

637
00:27:00,649 --> 00:27:01,589
isn't really clear to them,

638
00:27:01,589 --> 00:27:03,630
so they don't know what they're working towards.

639
00:27:03,630 --> 00:27:05,231
Or maybe they don't see how their work

640
00:27:05,231 --> 00:27:06,252
fits into that game vision, right?

641
00:27:06,252 --> 00:27:07,472
Maybe they're working on something

642
00:27:07,472 --> 00:27:10,234
that doesn't really support any of the pillars,

643
00:27:10,234 --> 00:27:10,974
so they don't understand how it fits.

644
00:27:10,974 --> 00:27:13,976
Or maybe they don't believe in your game vision.

645
00:27:13,976 --> 00:27:16,337
Maybe you're working on a game in a genre

646
00:27:16,337 --> 00:27:18,418
they don't respect or like.

647
00:27:18,418 --> 00:27:20,539
Or maybe they don't think the game you're making is good.

648
00:27:22,077 --> 00:27:23,997
Or maybe you or the leads on your team

649
00:27:23,997 --> 00:27:25,638
just don't have credibility,

650
00:27:25,638 --> 00:27:28,079
so that you tell them what the vision for the game is,

651
00:27:28,079 --> 00:27:29,600
and that, hey, you're working towards this thing

652
00:27:29,600 --> 00:27:31,261
that's really important, but they just don't believe you.

653
00:27:31,261 --> 00:27:34,782
One of the worst instances of this I ever saw,

654
00:27:34,782 --> 00:27:36,983
so I was on a project that had an enormous amount

655
00:27:36,983 --> 00:27:39,264
of pressure, right, and tons of ambiguity.

656
00:27:39,264 --> 00:27:41,365
The design for the game, the core design,

657
00:27:41,365 --> 00:27:42,745
kept changing really radically,

658
00:27:42,745 --> 00:27:45,086
and that meant that the design team was crunching

659
00:27:45,086 --> 00:27:47,327
to implement these changes into the levels

660
00:27:47,327 --> 00:27:49,468
and catch up with the balance changes

661
00:27:49,468 --> 00:27:51,049
and all the other major changes that were happening.

662
00:27:52,640 --> 00:27:55,943
So everyone was working crazy hours, tempers were high,

663
00:27:55,943 --> 00:27:58,725
stress was super high, people were having shouting matches

664
00:27:58,725 --> 00:28:01,187
on the floor over who wasn't doing their job.

665
00:28:01,187 --> 00:28:05,131
Years long friendships were dissolving, it was a mess.

666
00:28:05,131 --> 00:28:06,972
And in the middle of all of that, we had a team meeting.

667
00:28:06,972 --> 00:28:10,075
And one of the studio heads got up in front of everyone

668
00:28:10,075 --> 00:28:12,577
and said, hey, our plan is great,

669
00:28:12,577 --> 00:28:15,019
if you guys are crunching, it's your own fault

670
00:28:15,019 --> 00:28:15,920
for not planning well enough.

671
00:28:18,267 --> 00:28:21,650
And this happened over 10 years ago,

672
00:28:21,650 --> 00:28:24,233
and you can probably tell I'm still pretty upset about it.

673
00:28:24,233 --> 00:28:27,135
That was like a slap in the face, right?

674
00:28:27,135 --> 00:28:28,937
And not only because it was clear

675
00:28:28,937 --> 00:28:31,219
that our hard work wasn't being appreciated and respected,

676
00:28:31,219 --> 00:28:34,382
but also because either they didn't know

677
00:28:34,382 --> 00:28:35,923
we were crunching this hard,

678
00:28:35,923 --> 00:28:37,645
in which case we didn't trust them anymore,

679
00:28:37,645 --> 00:28:39,166
we didn't trust their judgment,

680
00:28:39,166 --> 00:28:41,629
or they knew and they just didn't care, right?

681
00:28:41,629 --> 00:28:43,050
And neither of those are great.

682
00:28:43,957 --> 00:28:47,119
Don't do this to your team, please.

683
00:28:47,119 --> 00:28:49,200
What can you do?

684
00:28:49,200 --> 00:28:52,683
What do I wish that my producer had done in this situation?

685
00:28:52,683 --> 00:28:54,884
First, be honest about what's happening.

686
00:28:54,884 --> 00:28:56,645
There are problems on your project.

687
00:28:56,645 --> 00:28:59,547
Be honest about them, because you need credibility

688
00:28:59,547 --> 00:29:01,128
with your team, and your team needs

689
00:29:01,128 --> 00:29:03,209
to know that you know what the problems are

690
00:29:03,209 --> 00:29:04,330
and that you're willing to talk about them.

691
00:29:04,330 --> 00:29:07,612
If that guy had stood up and said, look,

692
00:29:07,612 --> 00:29:08,592
we know you're working long hours.

693
00:29:08,592 --> 00:29:10,754
We know that things are super ambiguous right now,

694
00:29:10,754 --> 00:29:13,155
but we're working on it, and we appreciate what you're doing,

695
00:29:14,107 --> 00:29:16,908
It would have been a very different situation, right?

696
00:29:16,908 --> 00:29:19,490
I would have respected him a lot more,

697
00:29:19,490 --> 00:29:22,031
and the team would have been a lot happier.

698
00:29:22,031 --> 00:29:24,573
So just make sure that people's work is appreciated.

699
00:29:24,573 --> 00:29:26,814
Again, lazy people don't become game developers.

700
00:29:26,814 --> 00:29:28,395
People are going to put in a ton of work.

701
00:29:28,395 --> 00:29:29,356
So make sure they know that it's appreciated.

702
00:29:29,356 --> 00:29:30,797
Make sure it actually is appreciated.

703
00:29:30,797 --> 00:29:32,878
And then second, communicate critical information

704
00:29:32,878 --> 00:29:33,358
to your team.

705
00:29:33,358 --> 00:29:35,920
If there's something they need to know to do good work,

706
00:29:35,920 --> 00:29:37,221
make sure they're not the last to know it.

707
00:29:37,221 --> 00:29:39,222
Make sure that they know all the information they need.

708
00:29:39,222 --> 00:29:41,843
Again, ambiguity is when you don't have enough information.

709
00:29:41,843 --> 00:29:43,785
So make sure your team has as much information as possible.

710
00:29:46,924 --> 00:29:49,926
And then, if your team doesn't have trust in your plan,

711
00:29:49,926 --> 00:29:53,629
one way you can build trust is by executing your plan well,

712
00:29:53,629 --> 00:29:56,411
showing your team, look, this plan is working, right?

713
00:29:56,411 --> 00:29:58,673
We're getting closer to the game we want to make.

714
00:29:58,673 --> 00:29:59,614
Things are going well.

715
00:29:59,614 --> 00:30:01,855
The schedule resembles reality, right?

716
00:30:01,855 --> 00:30:03,597
Now, if the plan doesn't work, you have a problem,

717
00:30:03,597 --> 00:30:05,518
and maybe your team is right not to trust it,

718
00:30:05,518 --> 00:30:06,819
and they need to fix it.

719
00:30:06,819 --> 00:30:08,820
But if you have a good plan, execute it well.

720
00:30:08,820 --> 00:30:11,002
Be a good, strong producer so your team can rely on you

721
00:30:11,002 --> 00:30:13,884
and the plan and feel some more confidence

722
00:30:13,884 --> 00:30:14,605
in what's going to happen to them.

723
00:30:17,354 --> 00:30:19,915
And then keep your ears open for problems.

724
00:30:19,915 --> 00:30:22,157
Pull on little threads until you find out what's wrong.

725
00:30:22,157 --> 00:30:25,539
Remember that most of us are on teams

726
00:30:25,539 --> 00:30:28,020
full of nice, decent people.

727
00:30:28,020 --> 00:30:31,182
Most people do not want to complain or give you bad news.

728
00:30:31,182 --> 00:30:33,183
But to be a good producer, you need that bad news.

729
00:30:33,183 --> 00:30:35,104
You need to be able to know the problems on your team

730
00:30:35,104 --> 00:30:36,405
so that you can fix them.

731
00:30:36,405 --> 00:30:38,185
So if you hear someone complaining about

732
00:30:38,185 --> 00:30:41,267
how a design doesn't know what they're doing or expressing.

733
00:30:41,654 --> 00:30:44,517
a lack of confidence in your overall plan, pull on that.

734
00:30:44,517 --> 00:30:46,600
Find out what's underlying that.

735
00:30:46,600 --> 00:30:48,803
Maybe it's something real that you need to fix.

736
00:30:48,803 --> 00:30:55,390
And then last, work with your team to really assess the risks to your project.

737
00:30:55,390 --> 00:30:59,175
Your project is going to have risks and sitting down and really talking them out.

738
00:30:59,778 --> 00:31:02,080
And planning out what you would do if those things happened

739
00:31:02,080 --> 00:31:04,081
is a really valuable exercise.

740
00:31:04,081 --> 00:31:06,463
If you don't have a plan B, you don't really have a plan.

741
00:31:06,463 --> 00:31:09,125
And again, because there's so much ambiguity in game

742
00:31:09,125 --> 00:31:12,327
development, sometimes you need a plan C, D, E, F, et cetera

743
00:31:12,327 --> 00:31:13,368
also.

744
00:31:13,368 --> 00:31:16,550
So here's an example of a risk assessment.

745
00:31:16,550 --> 00:31:17,971
So this is when you sit down with your team

746
00:31:17,971 --> 00:31:19,713
or with your leads if you're on a big team.

747
00:31:20,821 --> 00:31:23,203
And you ask them, what are you afraid about?

748
00:31:23,203 --> 00:31:24,485
Like, what keeps you up at night?

749
00:31:24,485 --> 00:31:25,586
What are you afraid is gonna happen?

750
00:31:25,586 --> 00:31:27,948
And then you list those things, write them down.

751
00:31:27,948 --> 00:31:29,830
And then for each risk,

752
00:31:29,830 --> 00:31:31,391
talk about how likely it is to happen.

753
00:31:31,391 --> 00:31:34,074
And then what impact on your project

754
00:31:34,074 --> 00:31:35,095
would it have if it happened?

755
00:31:35,095 --> 00:31:36,456
How bad would it be if this happened?

756
00:31:36,456 --> 00:31:40,560
So, and then, you know, talk about a mitigation plan.

757
00:31:40,560 --> 00:31:41,941
What could you do if this happened?

758
00:31:41,941 --> 00:31:43,063
Or what can you do to prevent it?

759
00:31:44,034 --> 00:31:47,355
Not only is this going to make you feel like you have more control over your lives and

760
00:31:47,355 --> 00:31:50,417
over your situation, but it will actually give you more control over your lives and

761
00:31:50,417 --> 00:31:54,599
your situation because, again, you're developing information, you're creating information so

762
00:31:54,599 --> 00:31:56,220
that you have less ambiguity.

763
00:31:56,220 --> 00:32:00,283
A lot of publishers require an updated risk assessment like this with every milestone,

764
00:32:00,283 --> 00:32:01,623
and I think that's a really good idea.

765
00:32:01,623 --> 00:32:05,425
I think this is super valuable, and every project, I think, could benefit from this.

766
00:32:05,425 --> 00:32:06,726
Okay, number four, conflict and resentment.

767
00:32:12,456 --> 00:32:16,218
So, nice people are usually good at hiding problems, but sometimes those problems get

768
00:32:16,218 --> 00:32:21,001
so bad and so big that they blow up and, you know, again, cause everything from shouting

769
00:32:21,001 --> 00:32:25,624
matches on the floor or just long-term simmering resentment that makes it harder for your team

770
00:32:25,624 --> 00:32:26,204
to work together.

771
00:32:26,204 --> 00:32:31,507
And usually this is because of that combination of lots of ambiguity and tons of pressure.

772
00:32:31,507 --> 00:32:37,210
People don't behave well in those situations and they're going to want to lash out.

773
00:32:37,210 --> 00:32:38,211
It's human nature.

774
00:32:40,690 --> 00:32:46,534
Sometimes people on your team may be afraid to bring up ideas or ask questions in meetings

775
00:32:46,534 --> 00:32:52,678
because they're afraid of either being scapegoated, like being seen as the problem, or just that

776
00:32:52,678 --> 00:32:54,579
they won't be respected or listened to.

777
00:32:54,579 --> 00:32:55,660
And maybe that is actually happening.

778
00:32:55,660 --> 00:33:00,303
Maybe people on your team do get thrown under the bus if they're the ones bringing up problems,

779
00:33:00,303 --> 00:33:00,483
right?

780
00:33:02,543 --> 00:33:04,785
And these problems aren't always visible.

781
00:33:04,785 --> 00:33:09,629
Maybe there's just some invisible hidden resentment or fear or bad feelings and they're ready

782
00:33:09,629 --> 00:33:13,632
to erupt at any moment, but you're not really seeing them because, again, people are pretty

783
00:33:13,632 --> 00:33:14,633
good at hiding them.

784
00:33:14,633 --> 00:33:18,656
A friend of mine was a producer on a team that was under a ton of pressure to ship a

785
00:33:18,656 --> 00:33:20,357
launch title.

786
00:33:20,357 --> 00:33:22,459
The publisher's priorities kept changing pretty wildly.

787
00:33:23,324 --> 00:33:25,166
and the team was working super hard.

788
00:33:25,166 --> 00:33:28,208
Now, they did manage to ship, and they shipped a good game.

789
00:33:28,208 --> 00:33:30,250
And it was critically acclaimed, everyone was happy.

790
00:33:30,250 --> 00:33:33,072
It was like, okay, that's over, awesome, everything's great.

791
00:33:33,072 --> 00:33:35,334
And then the team did peer reviews.

792
00:33:36,533 --> 00:33:38,754
And all of these huge interpersonal

793
00:33:38,754 --> 00:33:40,656
and team dynamic problems just boiled up

794
00:33:40,656 --> 00:33:42,597
in these peer reviews, kind of out of nowhere.

795
00:33:42,597 --> 00:33:44,558
And the team leadership was like really surprised

796
00:33:44,558 --> 00:33:46,619
they didn't even know that any of this was there

797
00:33:46,619 --> 00:33:48,441
because the team was like a bunch of senior people

798
00:33:48,441 --> 00:33:49,722
who didn't want to rock the boat.

799
00:33:49,722 --> 00:33:52,203
They didn't want to distract from like this huge,

800
00:33:52,203 --> 00:33:53,944
you know, tons of pressure problem

801
00:33:53,944 --> 00:33:55,585
they had to ship this game.

802
00:33:55,585 --> 00:33:58,647
So the leadership also had been hyper-focused on shipping.

803
00:33:58,647 --> 00:34:00,629
So they really hadn't noticed that their team

804
00:34:00,629 --> 00:34:01,689
was completely falling apart

805
00:34:01,689 --> 00:34:03,871
because it was all happening kind of invisibly.

806
00:34:06,297 --> 00:34:09,540
Okay, so what can you do about this to prevent this from happening?

807
00:34:09,540 --> 00:34:11,341
First of all, doing peer reviews earlier.

808
00:34:11,341 --> 00:34:16,325
So peer reviews are when you have everyone on your team pick like three to five people

809
00:34:16,325 --> 00:34:19,908
and write a short kind of blurb about, okay, how is this person doing?

810
00:34:19,908 --> 00:34:20,969
What could they do better?

811
00:34:20,969 --> 00:34:22,370
Are there any problems with them?

812
00:34:22,370 --> 00:34:26,554
So this is something that you should do if you can.

813
00:34:26,554 --> 00:34:28,455
It's a good way to surface problems.

814
00:34:28,455 --> 00:34:29,416
It is difficult, though.

815
00:34:29,416 --> 00:34:30,697
First of all, it's time consuming.

816
00:34:31,381 --> 00:34:36,683
Second of all, if there are a lot of personal problems on your team, people may not be willing

817
00:34:36,683 --> 00:34:37,884
to attach their name to it.

818
00:34:37,884 --> 00:34:42,586
And third, you know, people do not want to hurt someone else's feelings.

819
00:34:42,586 --> 00:34:45,248
Nobody wants to be mean or raise problems.

820
00:34:45,248 --> 00:34:46,948
Most people don't.

821
00:34:47,509 --> 00:34:50,310
If you do these anonymously, anonymous reporting isn't great either.

822
00:34:50,310 --> 00:34:52,070
That can cause some problems too.

823
00:34:52,070 --> 00:34:53,390
But it's better than nothing.

824
00:34:53,390 --> 00:34:56,751
Like, if you have problems that are so big that no one on your team wants to speak up,

825
00:34:56,751 --> 00:35:00,012
anonymous reporting or anonymous peer reviews may help you find those problems.

826
00:35:00,012 --> 00:35:01,332
And again, they're better than nothing.

827
00:35:01,332 --> 00:35:04,912
Another better way, though, is one-on-ones.

828
00:35:04,912 --> 00:35:08,433
So this is when everyone on your team has someone that they trust and respect, that

829
00:35:08,433 --> 00:35:13,214
they talk to regularly, just, you know, the two of them, and they're able to surface problems

830
00:35:13,214 --> 00:35:16,095
and kind of chew over things and develop solutions.

831
00:35:17,685 --> 00:35:20,227
So even if you have a very small team with light management,

832
00:35:20,227 --> 00:35:21,849
it helps to make sure that everyone on your team

833
00:35:21,849 --> 00:35:23,250
has someone that they're talking to regularly,

834
00:35:23,250 --> 00:35:27,394
that they can, again, work with them to solve problems

835
00:35:27,394 --> 00:35:28,515
and just raise issues.

836
00:35:28,515 --> 00:35:30,777
And that helps people also feel like they're being heard

837
00:35:30,777 --> 00:35:32,479
and listened to and respected, which is important.

838
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:40,084
Second, if your team members aren't comfortable speaking out, you need to build psychological

839
00:35:40,084 --> 00:35:41,105
safety on your team.

840
00:35:41,105 --> 00:35:43,466
So this is something that Google did.

841
00:35:43,466 --> 00:35:45,128
It's called Project Aristotle.

842
00:35:45,128 --> 00:35:47,790
I'll link to it again in the notes, but you should look it up.

843
00:35:47,790 --> 00:35:51,653
Google looked at all of their teams and they looked at which teams performed really well

844
00:35:51,653 --> 00:35:54,015
and were super strong and which teams were underperforming.

845
00:35:54,015 --> 00:35:55,916
And they looked at correlating factors.

846
00:35:57,284 --> 00:36:02,028
And the strongest correlation they found was something they called psychological safety.

847
00:36:02,028 --> 00:36:07,713
And that's when people felt comfortable and safe expressing their feelings and ideas.

848
00:36:07,713 --> 00:36:09,234
Where everyone felt heard and respected.

849
00:36:09,234 --> 00:36:13,738
People didn't feel like they were being dismissed, people weren't being talked over in meetings.

850
00:36:13,738 --> 00:36:15,139
This is super, super important.

851
00:36:15,139 --> 00:36:18,381
You need to make sure that everyone on your team feels like they can express themselves

852
00:36:18,381 --> 00:36:21,724
without being, you know, disrespected or not listened to.

853
00:36:21,724 --> 00:36:24,026
So one thing you can do as a producer is in meetings.

854
00:36:24,366 --> 00:36:25,948
Make sure people aren't being talked over.

855
00:36:25,948 --> 00:36:27,830
Make sure people are being listened to.

856
00:36:27,830 --> 00:36:29,411
Make sure people know that they are respected

857
00:36:29,411 --> 00:36:30,912
and that their ideas are listened to.

858
00:36:30,912 --> 00:36:32,734
This is something that you can do

859
00:36:32,734 --> 00:36:34,896
and it's super, super valuable.

860
00:36:34,896 --> 00:36:38,540
Ask people who don't usually speak up for their input

861
00:36:38,540 --> 00:36:41,042
and then really listen to and respect what they have to say.

862
00:36:44,197 --> 00:36:47,439
And then, you know, third, yourself be trustworthy.

863
00:36:47,439 --> 00:36:49,480
So again, especially if there's tons of ambiguity

864
00:36:49,480 --> 00:36:52,382
on your project, make sure that there isn't any ambiguity

865
00:36:52,382 --> 00:36:55,523
about you, the producer, personally.

866
00:36:55,523 --> 00:36:57,224
You know, make sure people can trust you.

867
00:36:57,224 --> 00:36:59,406
Do what you say you're going to do

868
00:36:59,406 --> 00:37:00,707
when you say you're going to do it.

869
00:37:00,707 --> 00:37:03,768
This is actually a lot more rare than you might think,

870
00:37:03,768 --> 00:37:05,950
and as a producer, it will make you really, really valuable.

871
00:37:07,586 --> 00:37:10,388
Make sure that the information you're giving your team

872
00:37:10,388 --> 00:37:13,170
matches the information they're hearing other places.

873
00:37:13,170 --> 00:37:15,672
Make sure that people can really trust what you say.

874
00:37:15,672 --> 00:37:18,734
And part of that is if you don't know something,

875
00:37:18,734 --> 00:37:19,494
say you don't know it.

876
00:37:19,494 --> 00:37:21,996
Like be comfortable saying, I don't know.

877
00:37:21,996 --> 00:37:23,117
I don't know, but I'll find out, right?

878
00:37:23,117 --> 00:37:24,417
Don't pretend you know something when you don't.

879
00:37:24,417 --> 00:37:25,198
People see through that.

880
00:37:25,198 --> 00:37:27,680
It'll eat away at your credibility

881
00:37:27,680 --> 00:37:30,682
if you pretend you know things that you don't.

882
00:37:30,682 --> 00:37:33,043
And you really need credibility as a producer

883
00:37:33,043 --> 00:37:34,384
to be able to solve any of these problems.

884
00:37:36,833 --> 00:37:40,815
And then last, make sure that the ownership areas of your project are super clear.

885
00:37:40,815 --> 00:37:45,637
You as the producer can't make sure the right work is getting done if you don't know who

886
00:37:45,637 --> 00:37:47,497
is ultimately responsible for that work.

887
00:37:47,497 --> 00:37:53,700
So you should know who owns every single feature or level or character or API integration on

888
00:37:53,700 --> 00:37:56,861
your project and really you should be able to sit down and write it down.

889
00:37:56,861 --> 00:37:59,462
So here's an example of an ownership list.

890
00:38:00,613 --> 00:38:04,276
And these can be as detailed or high level as you want,

891
00:38:04,276 --> 00:38:05,817
but if you couldn't right now sit down

892
00:38:05,817 --> 00:38:07,719
and generate this list for your project,

893
00:38:07,719 --> 00:38:09,000
then you have a problem as a producer.

894
00:38:09,000 --> 00:38:11,162
You should be able to make this.

895
00:38:11,162 --> 00:38:13,464
Secondly, if you make this list

896
00:38:13,464 --> 00:38:14,625
and it's just like the same name

897
00:38:14,625 --> 00:38:16,967
over and over and over and over for everything,

898
00:38:16,967 --> 00:38:19,089
and you don't have a one person project,

899
00:38:19,089 --> 00:38:21,391
then you do have a problem, right?

900
00:38:21,391 --> 00:38:23,092
Anyone who has ownership over something

901
00:38:23,092 --> 00:38:25,054
needs to be able to make decisions about it,

902
00:38:25,054 --> 00:38:26,435
and they're responsible for getting it done.

903
00:38:27,643 --> 00:38:32,225
There's no reason to hire really smart and motivated and creative people if you're not

904
00:38:32,225 --> 00:38:36,086
going to give them actual ownership over the work they're doing and control over it.

905
00:38:36,086 --> 00:38:40,688
There are people who just want to follow directions and do what they're told and they're way cheaper

906
00:38:40,688 --> 00:38:41,728
and sometimes easier to manage.

907
00:38:41,728 --> 00:38:42,889
So just hire those people.

908
00:38:42,889 --> 00:38:43,369
Save your money.

909
00:38:43,369 --> 00:38:47,130
If you're not going to give people ownership over their work, don't hire awesome creative

910
00:38:47,130 --> 00:38:48,631
people because they'd rather work somewhere else anyway.

911
00:38:48,631 --> 00:38:48,891
All right.

912
00:38:48,891 --> 00:38:49,251
Last, indecision.

913
00:38:53,867 --> 00:38:56,568
So I'm gonna say it again, ambiguity is when you don't

914
00:38:56,568 --> 00:38:58,589
have enough information to make decisions.

915
00:38:58,589 --> 00:39:00,450
So naturally, when there's lots of ambiguity,

916
00:39:00,450 --> 00:39:01,650
people are gonna wanna not make decisions

917
00:39:01,650 --> 00:39:03,971
because they don't wanna make the wrong decision, right?

918
00:39:03,971 --> 00:39:06,632
But you have to make all of your decisions

919
00:39:06,632 --> 00:39:08,053
to ship your game.

920
00:39:08,053 --> 00:39:10,154
So indecision is gonna keep you from shipping.

921
00:39:10,154 --> 00:39:11,094
And the most common problem is this kind of

922
00:39:11,094 --> 00:39:12,875
unspecified delay.

923
00:39:12,875 --> 00:39:18,517
This is when people want more time to think

924
00:39:18,517 --> 00:39:21,058
before making a decision, but they don't really know

925
00:39:21,058 --> 00:39:22,658
how much time that's gonna take.

926
00:39:23,774 --> 00:39:25,796
They might be waiting for inspiration.

927
00:39:25,796 --> 00:39:27,638
They might be waiting for something to happen

928
00:39:27,638 --> 00:39:29,520
that could help force them to make the decision,

929
00:39:29,520 --> 00:39:31,422
but they don't really know what it is.

930
00:39:31,422 --> 00:39:35,346
They might be afraid of the consequences of their decision.

931
00:39:35,346 --> 00:39:38,869
So again, if you're working within really tight budget

932
00:39:38,869 --> 00:39:41,072
or schedule or future constraints,

933
00:39:41,072 --> 00:39:42,253
this can be a big problem.

934
00:39:42,253 --> 00:39:45,076
Maybe the person making the decision

935
00:39:45,076 --> 00:39:46,757
isn't really qualified to do it.

936
00:39:47,854 --> 00:39:50,516
So remember the ownership list we were just talking about.

937
00:39:50,516 --> 00:39:53,178
Maybe the person owning art decisions

938
00:39:53,178 --> 00:39:54,198
isn't a very good artist.

939
00:39:54,198 --> 00:39:57,381
Or maybe your lead designer isn't familiar

940
00:39:57,381 --> 00:39:59,322
with the genre you're working in.

941
00:39:59,322 --> 00:40:01,564
Or maybe someone's trying to make engineering decisions

942
00:40:01,564 --> 00:40:03,185
because they were a programmer like 15 years ago,

943
00:40:03,185 --> 00:40:04,326
but they don't really know what they're doing,

944
00:40:04,326 --> 00:40:06,067
and so they kind of just wait until they know

945
00:40:06,067 --> 00:40:09,010
what's the right decision, but they never will.

946
00:40:10,969 --> 00:40:13,452
Or maybe you're lucky and it's hard to make decisions

947
00:40:13,452 --> 00:40:16,295
because you just have way too many good options.

948
00:40:16,295 --> 00:40:18,817
Maybe your design vision has eight awesome pillars

949
00:40:18,817 --> 00:40:21,460
and they're all so good that you don't wanna cut any of them.

950
00:40:21,460 --> 00:40:23,122
But you know that you have to to ship,

951
00:40:23,122 --> 00:40:24,043
but you just can't bring yourself

952
00:40:24,043 --> 00:40:26,385
to cut any of these awesome features.

953
00:40:26,385 --> 00:40:28,608
That's not the worst situation in the world to be in,

954
00:40:28,608 --> 00:40:29,869
but it will keep you from shipping

955
00:40:29,869 --> 00:40:30,890
just as much as everything else.

956
00:40:34,412 --> 00:40:38,676
So ironically, I'm on a super ambiguous project right now,

957
00:40:38,676 --> 00:40:40,318
but I don't have to deal with this very much

958
00:40:40,318 --> 00:40:43,241
because my project director has this philosophy

959
00:40:43,241 --> 00:40:45,944
where all decisions are easy.

960
00:40:45,944 --> 00:40:47,686
If it's an easy decision, you just make it.

961
00:40:47,686 --> 00:40:49,588
And if it's a hard decision, it's hard

962
00:40:49,588 --> 00:40:51,310
because both options are about equally good,

963
00:40:51,310 --> 00:40:51,990
so you just pick one.

964
00:40:55,958 --> 00:41:00,182
Now, I really like this because not only does it make it way easier for me to do my producer

965
00:41:00,182 --> 00:41:05,787
job well, but also because it's kind of this interesting yardstick I can use.

966
00:41:05,787 --> 00:41:08,629
If we're facing a hard decision, like, why is this one hard?

967
00:41:08,629 --> 00:41:13,594
If all decisions are easy, then what's unique about this decision that makes it really hard

968
00:41:13,594 --> 00:41:14,594
to make?

969
00:41:14,594 --> 00:41:15,475
You know, is it...

970
00:41:15,475 --> 00:41:18,978
Why does it not fall into one of those two categories of, like, either it's easy or it's

971
00:41:18,978 --> 00:41:19,719
hard so it's easy?

972
00:41:21,410 --> 00:41:24,612
Is it because both options are really good,

973
00:41:24,612 --> 00:41:26,673
and you don't want to let either one go?

974
00:41:26,673 --> 00:41:30,815
Then you as the producer need to drive that decision.

975
00:41:30,815 --> 00:41:32,677
And you can do that with data.

976
00:41:32,677 --> 00:41:34,738
You have to say, look, our schedule dictates,

977
00:41:34,738 --> 00:41:36,239
like the laws of physics dictate

978
00:41:36,239 --> 00:41:37,439
that we have to decide this now.

979
00:41:37,439 --> 00:41:38,960
We just have to pick something.

980
00:41:38,960 --> 00:41:42,102
Have data, be really dogged about this.

981
00:41:42,102 --> 00:41:44,063
And again, the more critical this decision is,

982
00:41:44,063 --> 00:41:45,504
the more it's holding up your project,

983
00:41:45,504 --> 00:41:48,046
the more energy you have to put in to make sure it gets made.

984
00:41:50,548 --> 00:41:52,490
Or is it because all possible decisions

985
00:41:52,490 --> 00:41:54,171
are really gonna hurt your game or your team?

986
00:41:54,171 --> 00:41:56,453
Maybe all the possible decisions are really bad,

987
00:41:56,453 --> 00:42:00,335
and so the decision maker is just super reluctant, right?

988
00:42:00,335 --> 00:42:04,198
You know, then your risk mitigation plan

989
00:42:04,198 --> 00:42:05,158
can be really helpful.

990
00:42:05,158 --> 00:42:07,240
Is there a way to assign numbers

991
00:42:07,240 --> 00:42:08,801
to how bad these decisions are, right?

992
00:42:08,801 --> 00:42:10,322
If both options are terrible,

993
00:42:10,322 --> 00:42:11,963
maybe one of them is slightly less terrible,

994
00:42:11,963 --> 00:42:14,365
and then you can pick that one.

995
00:42:14,365 --> 00:42:16,306
You know, is there a way to mitigate

996
00:42:16,306 --> 00:42:17,747
one of the, you know, some of the fallout

997
00:42:17,747 --> 00:42:18,588
from one of the options?

998
00:42:19,493 --> 00:42:21,855
And again, it's almost always better

999
00:42:21,855 --> 00:42:24,918
to make the decision early rather than put it off.

1000
00:42:24,918 --> 00:42:27,120
Almost always the longer you put off a decision,

1001
00:42:27,120 --> 00:42:27,580
the worse it gets.

1002
00:42:27,580 --> 00:42:30,642
Or is it hard because the person making the decision

1003
00:42:30,642 --> 00:42:33,164
just really doesn't have enough expertise in the area

1004
00:42:33,164 --> 00:42:34,886
or enough information to make it, right?

1005
00:42:34,886 --> 00:42:37,308
In this case, maybe you either need to change

1006
00:42:37,308 --> 00:42:41,271
who owns that decision or educate yourselves, right?

1007
00:42:41,271 --> 00:42:43,293
Maybe that person can become an expert in this area.

1008
00:42:44,512 --> 00:42:47,876
You can have tools like play tests or competitive analysis,

1009
00:42:47,876 --> 00:42:50,259
like do market research, bring in users,

1010
00:42:50,259 --> 00:42:53,283
have them talk to whoever's making the decision.

1011
00:42:53,283 --> 00:42:56,126
I was on a team where we were working on a game genre

1012
00:42:56,126 --> 00:42:58,089
that the lead designer had never worked in before.

1013
00:42:58,828 --> 00:43:01,349
So we played a bunch of games in that genre together

1014
00:43:01,349 --> 00:43:04,031
and just looked at, OK, what makes these games good?

1015
00:43:04,031 --> 00:43:04,891
What do we like about them?

1016
00:43:04,891 --> 00:43:06,392
What don't we like about them?

1017
00:43:06,392 --> 00:43:08,333
If you're making a kid's puzzle game

1018
00:43:08,333 --> 00:43:11,514
and your lead designer has only done hardcore strategy games,

1019
00:43:11,514 --> 00:43:12,355
bring in some kids.

1020
00:43:12,355 --> 00:43:13,875
Talk to them about what games they like.

1021
00:43:13,875 --> 00:43:15,576
Look at a bunch of kids' puzzle games.

1022
00:43:15,576 --> 00:43:17,477
See what is it about those games that people fall in love with

1023
00:43:17,477 --> 00:43:18,378
and what you can focus on.

1024
00:43:21,627 --> 00:43:24,188
And then last, as a producer, you're in a powerful position

1025
00:43:24,188 --> 00:43:27,049
where you can kind of propose a decision out loud.

1026
00:43:27,049 --> 00:43:29,109
Often as the producer, you're less kind of married

1027
00:43:29,109 --> 00:43:30,090
to the outcome of the decision,

1028
00:43:30,090 --> 00:43:32,150
because your goal is to get the game done.

1029
00:43:32,150 --> 00:43:34,031
So maybe you can say like, hey, we should do this.

1030
00:43:34,031 --> 00:43:36,111
Sometimes a decision maker just needs to hear someone

1031
00:43:36,111 --> 00:43:37,812
say it out loud and then respond and like,

1032
00:43:37,812 --> 00:43:41,193
oh, I agree with you, or no, I disagree with you.

1033
00:43:41,193 --> 00:43:42,993
Now, be very careful here.

1034
00:43:44,033 --> 00:43:46,594
Because as a producer, your job is not to make decisions,

1035
00:43:46,594 --> 00:43:48,075
it's to get them made.

1036
00:43:48,075 --> 00:43:49,816
I've seen a lot of times where producers

1037
00:43:49,816 --> 00:43:51,477
will kind of try to jump into this gap

1038
00:43:51,477 --> 00:43:54,219
because there's a hole in ownership.

1039
00:43:54,219 --> 00:43:56,620
And it basically doesn't ever work out.

1040
00:43:56,620 --> 00:43:58,842
It's kind of a temporary fix.

1041
00:43:58,842 --> 00:44:00,062
It can cause more problems than it solves,

1042
00:44:00,062 --> 00:44:02,384
so be careful with that.

1043
00:44:02,384 --> 00:44:04,245
You should be getting decisions made, though.

1044
00:44:04,245 --> 00:44:04,865
That's your goal.

1045
00:44:04,865 --> 00:44:06,966
So one way you can do that, this is a backlog.

1046
00:44:06,966 --> 00:44:11,049
So basically, you take all the features you want to make,

1047
00:44:11,049 --> 00:44:12,830
and you just put them in a list.

1048
00:44:12,830 --> 00:44:13,350
You order them.

1049
00:44:14,092 --> 00:44:16,073
And this is one of the core tenants of Scrum.

1050
00:44:16,073 --> 00:44:19,475
So this backlog actually is from a project I was on,

1051
00:44:19,475 --> 00:44:21,556
which was in the too much good stuff scenario,

1052
00:44:21,556 --> 00:44:23,877
where we just had too many good things we wanted to make.

1053
00:44:23,877 --> 00:44:25,878
Any of them could make our project successful.

1054
00:44:25,878 --> 00:44:26,979
We couldn't really decide.

1055
00:44:26,979 --> 00:44:28,960
So I just listed everything in order.

1056
00:44:28,960 --> 00:44:30,601
And I gave it to the project director,

1057
00:44:30,601 --> 00:44:32,282
and I was like, look, reorder this.

1058
00:44:32,282 --> 00:44:33,442
Do whatever you want with this list.

1059
00:44:33,442 --> 00:44:34,643
You own it.

1060
00:44:34,643 --> 00:44:35,764
But it has to have an order.

1061
00:44:35,764 --> 00:44:36,544
It has to be sequential.

1062
00:44:36,544 --> 00:44:37,685
And then we're gonna start at the top,

1063
00:44:37,685 --> 00:44:38,345
and we're gonna work down.

1064
00:44:40,466 --> 00:44:43,827
So if your team just isn't making important decisions,

1065
00:44:43,827 --> 00:44:46,028
starting with a backlog can be really powerful.

1066
00:44:46,028 --> 00:44:48,309
If nothing else, it's gonna force you to confront

1067
00:44:48,309 --> 00:44:52,551
